A lovely taco spot inside Domino Park, right on the East River. It’s a lovely spot for some al fresco tacos ($4 - $5) and margaritas ($10) or beers ($7). There are only two vegetarian taco options (cheese and mushrooms, or a double cheese taco with crispy cheese) but the elote ($5) and guacamole & chips ($8) are also meat free. The elote has a nice kick to it, the tacos could’ve used a bit more seasoning but the hot sauces provided are great and the self-serve limes and radishes are a nice touch.  If you want to avoid long lines, go there during the week - I didn’t have to wait at the cashier and my food was ready in less than ten minutes. Super friendly service. Thank you :)

Taco Cina is a riverside taco stand located inside Domino Park that includes traditional Tex-Mex dishes with a pronounced Brooklyn interpretation. While the views and location are truly the star of this no frills eatery however a few dishes do the heavy lifting for the restuarant. The standard taco offerings are slightly above average but provide fun twists that offer options for all diets. If you are going to order one item off the menu make it the Cojita and Monterey Jack taco which features a crispy cheese shell with gooey cheese filling, arguably the best thing at Taco Cina. This isn't a destination worth a special trip alone but when combined with Domino Park the synergy makes it amazing.

I also got the rose in a can. Hit the spot.

We went on a busy Saturday, but the line moved relatively quickly and food came out in a reasonable amount of time. The food was all quite good and the location is fantastic.  Why the restaurant is receiving only one star is because of the careless attitude they took towards my girlfriend's shellfish allergy. We were very clear with the young lady taking the order that there was a shellfish allergy in the order and we double checked all of the items she ordered to make sure they were all safe. One of the members of our group ordered a shrimp taco, and we asked them to make sure that it was separate from the rest of the food. When we went to the window to pick the food up, the shrimp taco was sitting on top of the rest of the food we had ordered. When I attempted to ask them to clarify if care was taken to make sure her food was fine, they casually passed it off and said it was fine. My girlfriend, who is not all that sensitive, wound up having a reaction to the rest of the food.  I would recommend avoiding the restaurant if you have any sensitivities or allergies. We were extremely excited for the experience, as we love Danny Meyer's restaurants, but this was an extraordinary disappointment and brings up many concerns about their care and attitude towards allergies, which can be life and death for many.
